#Plot graphs for data visualization

library(DataExplorer)
plot_histogram(df)

plot_bar(df)

plot_density(df)

plot_boxplot(df, by= 'smoking' )

Histogram and density plots show the data distribution of non-factor data type columns. From the histogram, it is shown that there is a gap in between each bar for age, height.cm, urine.protein, and weight.kg variables. Cholesterol, fasting blood sugar, HDL, LDL, relaxation, systolic, waist.cm show a Gaussian distribution. On the other hand, hemoglobin histogram is slightly left-skewed whereas triglyceride is right-skewed.

The bar plots show that oral has only one input value throughout the entire dataset. Thus, this variable should be dropped. Furthermore, it is confirmed that hearing.left, hearing.right, dental.cares and smoking have only 2 unique values. Therefore, these columns should be converted to factor data type.

From the boxplots, there are outliers in fasting blood sugar, triglyceride, HDL, LDL.

#check correlation between continuous variables

plot_correlation(df,'continuous', cor_args = list("use" = "pairwise.complete.obs"))

####################################Generate Missing Data for Method Exploration#######################

#generate MCAR missing data

set.seed(100)
df_na<- delete_MCAR(df,0.01, c('gender', 'hemoglobin', 'ALT','serum.creatinine'))

#Missing Values Plot 1: Missing Data Plot with DataExplorer

#view and count missing values 
plot_missing(df_na)

There are 1% of missing data in age, hemoglobin, serum creatinine, alt and oral variables.

Plot 2: VIM plot

vim_plot<- aggr(df_na, numbers=TRUE, prop= c(TRUE, FALSE),cex.axis=0.5)

As shown in the VIM_plot, 1% of missing values have been introduced in each feature. Some observations have missing values in multiple features. More explanation!

******************************************Data Preparation******************************************** #Missing Data Treatment ##Imputation with missForest

Ref: https://rpubs.com/lmorgan95/MissForest#:~:text=MissForest%20is%20a%20random%20forest,then%20predicts%20the%20missing%20part. https://academic.oup.com/bioinformatics/article/28/1/112/219101 https://rstudio-pubs-static.s3.amazonaws.com/654183_b0991094b9354611b5c67ab4dbd07b04.html

#Imputation with missForest doParallel::registerDoParallel(cores = 8) # set based on number of CPU cores doRNG::registerDoRNG(seed = 123) dr <- missForest(df_na, parallelize = forests, maxiter=2, ntree=20, verbose=TRUE) imputed_df<- dr\(ximp sum(is.na(imputed_df)) dr\)OOBerror

#output processed data to csv file path<- C:/Users/TSL/Documents/APU/Applied Machine Learning/assignment/imputed_data.csv write.csv(imputed_df, file=path)

imputed_df<-read.csv('Imputed_data.csv',stringsAsFactors = TRUE)

#Removing the target variable. This is enable scaling of the independent variables

#change column names to lower case
colnames(imputed_df)<-tolower(colnames(imputed_df))
#exclude ID, eyesight(left, right), hearing(left, right), urine.protein, dental.caries, and oral columns
imputed_df <- imputed_df %>% select(-c(x,id,eyesight.left.,eyesight.right.,hearing.left.,
        hearing.right.,urine.protein,dental.caries,oral))
#convert target variable to factor data type
imputed_df$smoking<- as.factor(imputed_df$smoking)

*************************************************************outliers********************************************************************** #remove outliers for fasting blood sugar, triglyceride, HDL, LDL

hdl_outlier<-imputed_df[which(imputed_df$hdl >300), ]

#combine all rows with outliers
outliers<-rbind(hdl_outlier,fbs_outlier,triglyceride_outlier,chol_outlier,
      systolic_outlier,alt_outlier,ast_outlier)

#remove outliers from data frame
dfclean<- anti_join(imputed_df, outliers)
## Joining, by = c("gender", "age", "height.cm.", "weight.kg.", "waist.cm.",
## "systolic", "relaxation", "fasting.blood.sugar", "cholesterol", "triglyceride",
## "hdl", "ldl", "hemoglobin", "serum.creatinine", "ast", "alt", "gtp", "tartar",
## "smoking")

#data manipulation after removing outliers

#exclude target variable
df1 <- dfclean[,-19]
#extract target variable
smoking<- dfclean[,19]
#extract numeric variables
numVar<- !sapply(df1, is.factor)
#extract factor variable
factorVar<- sapply(df1, is.factor)
#convert target variable to label for XGboost
smoking_label<- as.integer(smoking)-1

#peform one-hot encoding on factor variable for XGBoost model

#peform one-hot encoding 
one_hot<- dummify(df1[factorVar], maxcat=5L)

*****************************************WITH ONE-HOT ENCODING***************************************************** #combine new dataset for xgb

oh_dfclean<-cbind(one_hot, df1[numVar], smoking_label)

****************************split data into training and test sets using stratified sampling *****************************************

#split data into training and test sets

#set seed to fix randomness
set.seed(123)
#split the data into training and validation sets by stratified sampling
split<- sample.split(dfclean$smoking, SplitRatio=0.7)
training<- subset(dfclean, split==TRUE)
test<- subset(dfclean, split==FALSE)

#split one-hot encoded data into training and test sets

#set seed to fix randomness
set.seed(123)
#split the data into training and validation sets by stratified sampling
split<- sample.split(oh_dfclean$smoking, SplitRatio=0.7)
oh_training<- subset(oh_dfclean, split==TRUE)
oh_test<- subset(oh_dfclean, split==FALSE)

#check class distribution

#Create Prediction and Model Evaluation Functions to be called

#function for prediction and confusion matrix
modelCM<-function(model, data){
  set.seed(100)
  pred<- predict(model,data[,-19], type='class')
  confusionMatrix(pred, data$smoking)
}

#function for ROC plot and AUC
ROCauc<- function (model, data){
  set.seed(100)
  pred_ROC= predict(model, type='prob', data[,-19])[,2]
  pred= prediction(pred_ROC, data$smoking)
  perf= performance(pred,'tpr', 'fpr')
  plot(perf, colorize=T,
       main='ROC Curve',
       ylab= 'Sensitivity',
       xlab= 'Specificity',
       print.cutoffs.at=seq(0,1,0.3),
       text.adj= c(-0.2,1.7))
  auc= as.numeric(performance(pred, 'auc')@y.values)
  auc=round(auc,3)
  print(paste('AUC:', auc))
}

#predict and evaluate on training set

#Model 1: basic model

#build basic model
library(randomForest)
set.seed(100)
rf1<- randomForest(smoking~.,data = training)
print(rf1)
## 
## Call:
##  randomForest(formula = smoking ~ ., data = training) 
##                Type of random forest: classification
##                      Number of trees: 500
## No. of variables tried at each split: 4
## 
##         OOB estimate of  error rate: 17.75%
## Confusion matrix:
##       0     1 class.error
## 0 20778  3880   0.1573526
## 1  3036 11273   0.2121742

For classification, there are two variable importance measures in random forest. The first measure is the Out-of-bag error (OOB). OOB error rate measures the prediction error of random forest and other models which use bootstrap aggregation. Thus, the OOB estimate of error rate is a useful measure to decide on different random forest classifiers.The goal should be selecting the model that produces the samllest OOB error rate. The second measure is the Gini index which measures the total decrease in node impurity. The basic random forest used 500 trees and 4 variables in each split (mtry) to build the classifier. The OOB estimate of error rate for this model is 17.75%, which means that out of the total number of observations, 17.55% (6838) of the observations in this training set were misclassified.

#functions to be called

#function for model evaluation
modelCM<-function(model, data){
  pred<- predict(model,data[,-19], type='class')
  confusionMatrix(pred, data$smoking, mode='everything')
}

#function for ROC plot and AUC
ROCauc<- function (model, data){
  pred_ROC= predict(model, data[,-19], type='prob')[,2]
  pred= prediction(pred_ROC, data$smoking)
  perf= performance(pred,'tpr', 'fpr')
  plot(perf, colorize=T,
       main='ROC Curve',
       ylab= 'Sensitivity',
       xlab= 'Specificity',
       print.cutoffs.at=seq(0,1,0.3),
       text.adj= c(-0.2,1.7))
  auc= as.numeric(performance(pred, 'auc')@y.values)
  auc=round(auc,3)
  print(paste('AUC:', auc))
}

#predict and evaluate model with training set

Model 2, ntree=2000 In RF model, multiple hyperparameters can be tuned to increase performance of the model. These include ntree (the number of trees in the forest), mtry (the number of variables randomly selected at each split, mtry is the sqrt of number of features when performing classification), nodesize (maximum number size of terminal nodes. Large number causes smaller trees to be grown).maxnodes (the maximum number of terminal nodes in the forest).

Different approaches of tuning the hyperparameter is available. The following approach uses tuneRF function to determine the best mtry hyperparmeter.

#build basic model
library(randomForest)
set.seed(100)
rf2<- randomForest(smoking~.,data = training, ntree=2000)
print(rf2)

#Model 3: Tune mtry #use tuneRF to determine hyperparameter mtry

set.seed(100)
mtry <- tuneRF(training[-19],training$smoking, 
               ntreeTry=2000,
               stepFactor=1.5,
               improve=1e-5, 
               trace=TRUE,
               plot=TRUE)
## mtry = 4  OOB error = 17.59% 
## Searching left ...
## mtry = 3     OOB error = 17.53% 
## 0.003647505 1e-05 
## mtry = 2     OOB error = 17.55% 
## -0.001610778 1e-05 
## Searching right ...
## mtry = 6     OOB error = 17.54% 
## -0.0008786059 1e-05

best.m <- mtry[mtry[, 2] == min(mtry[, 2]), 1]
print(mtry)

## 2.OOB    2 0.1755331
## 3.OOB    3 0.1752509
## 4.OOB    4 0.1758924
## 6.OOB    6 0.1754048
print(best.m)
## [1] 3

********************************************XGBoost************************************************************

XGBoost Extreme Gradient Boosting is one of the boosting ensemble method. it has both linear model and tree learning algorithms. Hence, XGBoost only works with numeric vectors, the categorical variables are converted into numeric vector through one hot encoding.

XGBoost uses a specific data structure (known as DMatrix) to store data

library(xgboost)
## Warning: package 'xgboost' was built under R version 4.2.3
## 
## Attaching package: 'xgboost'
## The following object is masked from 'package:dplyr':
## 
##     slice
set.seed(100)

#define predictor and response variables in training set
train_x<- data.matrix(oh_training[, -21])
train_y<- oh_training[, 21]

#define predictor and response variables in tet set
test_x<- data.matrix(oh_test[, -21])
test_y<- oh_test[,21 ]


#define final training and test sets
xgb_train<- xgb.DMatrix(train_x, label=train_y)
xgb_test<- xgb.DMatrix(data= test_x, label=test_y)

#Model 1

#build the model

xgb1<- xgboost( data= train_x, label=train_y,
                     nround=10, max_depth=5, eta=0.5, nthread=2,
                     objective='binary:logistic')

#Hyperparameter Tuning through cross validation

set.seed(100)
# set up all the pairwise combinations

xgb_grid = expand.grid(nrounds = c(500,1000),
                       max_depth=c(5,8,12),
                       eta= c(0.0001,0.001),
                       gamma=3,
                       colsample_bytree=0.5,
                       min_child_weight=5,
                       subsample=0.5)

#use cross validation
xgb_trcontrol = trainControl(method = "cv",
                             number = 5,
                             verboseIter = TRUE,
                             returnData = FALSE,
                             returnResamp = "all", 
                             allowParallel = TRUE)

xgb_cv= train(x = train_x,
                  y = as.factor(train_y),
                  trControl = xgb_trcontrol,
                  tuneGrid = xgb_grid,
                  method = "xgbTree")

Prediction and evaluation on training set

#predict using training set
xgb3pred_tr <- predict(xgb3, train_x)
#transform them in a 0 1 variable
xgb3pred_tr<- as.numeric(xgb3pred_tr>0.5)
confusionMatrix(factor(xgb3pred_tr),factor(train_y))
## Confusion Matrix and Statistics
## 
##           Reference
## Prediction     0     1
##          0 20724  2454
##          1  3934 11855
##                                           
##                Accuracy : 0.8361          
##                  95% CI : (0.8324, 0.8397)
##     No Information Rate : 0.6328          
##     P-Value [Acc > NIR] : < 2.2e-16       
##                                           
##                   Kappa : 0.6547          
##                                           
##  Mcnemar's Test P-Value : < 2.2e-16       
##                                           
##             Sensitivity : 0.8405          
##             Specificity : 0.8285          
##          Pos Pred Value : 0.8941          
##          Neg Pred Value : 0.7508          
##              Prevalence : 0.6328          
##          Detection Rate : 0.5318          
##    Detection Prevalence : 0.5948          
##       Balanced Accuracy : 0.8345          
##                                           
##        'Positive' Class : 0               
##

#ROC plot and AUC

xgb3pred_tr_ROC= predict(xgb3, train_x, type='prob')
xgb3pred_tr= prediction(xgb3pred_tr_ROC, train_y)
perf= performance(xgb3pred_tr,'tpr', 'fpr')
plot(perf, colorize=T,
       main='ROC Curve',
       ylab= 'Sensitivity',
       xlab= 'Specificity',
       print.cutoffs.at=seq(0,1,0.3),
       text.adj= c(-0.2,1.7))

auc= as.numeric(performance(xgb3pred_tr, 'auc')@y.values)
auc=round(auc,3)
print(paste('AUC:', auc))
## [1] "AUC: 0.912"

#Prediction and evaluation on test set

#predict using training set
xgb3pred_ts <- predict(xgb3, test_x)
#transform them in a 0 1 variable
xgb3pred_ts<- as.numeric(xgb3pred_ts>0.5)
confusionMatrix(factor(xgb3pred_ts),factor(test_y))

#ROC plot and AUC

xgb3pred_ts_ROC= predict(xgb3, test_x, type='prob')
xgb3pred_ts= prediction(xgb3pred_ts_ROC, test_y)
perf= performance(xgb3pred_ts,'tpr', 'fpr')
plot(perf, colorize=T,
       main='ROC Curve',
       ylab= 'Sensitivity',
       xlab= 'Specificity',
       print.cutoffs.at=seq(0,1,0.3),
       text.adj= c(-0.2,1.7))

auc= as.numeric(performance(xgb3pred_ts, 'auc')@y.values)
auc=round(auc,3)
print(paste('AUC:', auc))
## [1] "AUC: 0.855"

#compare xgb models

xgb1_pred_prob= predict(xgb1, test_x, type='prob')
xgb1_pred= prediction(xgb1_pred_prob, test_y)
xgb1_perf= performance(xgb1_pred,'tpr', 'fpr')
plot(xgb1_perf, col='blue', lwd=2, main='ROC Curves for XGBoost Models' )

xgb2_pred_prob= predict(xgb2, test_x, type='prob')
xgb2_pred= prediction(xgb2_pred_prob, test_y)
xgb2_perf= performance(xgb2_pred,'tpr', 'fpr')
plot(xgb2_perf, col='red', lwd=2, add=TRUE )

xgb3_pred_prob= predict(xgb3, test_x, type='prob')
xgb3_pred= prediction(xgb3_pred_prob, test_y)
xgb3_perf= performance(xgb3_pred,'tpr', 'fpr')
plot(xgb3_perf, col='green', lwd=2, add=TRUE )

legend('bottomright', legend=c('Model1', 'Model2', 'Model3'), col=c('blue', 'red', 'green'), lwd=2, cex=0.8)

#Combine the best model of each method

rf_pred_prob<- predict(rf3, type='prob', test[, -19])[,2]
rf_pred<- prediction(rf_pred_prob,test$smoking)
rf_perf= performance(rf_pred, 'tpr','fpr')
plot(rf_perf, col='red', lwd=4, main='ROC Curves for Decision Tree, Random Forest and XGBoost')

dt_pred_prob<- predict(dt3, type='prob',test[, -19])[,2]
dt_pred= prediction(dt_pred_prob, test$smoking)
dt_perf= performance(dt_pred, 'tpr','fpr')
plot(dt_perf, col='blue', lwd=2, add=TRUE)

xgb_pred_prob= predict(xgb2, test_x, type='prob')
xgb_pred= prediction(xgb_pred_prob, test_y)
xgb_perf= performance(xgb_pred,'tpr', 'fpr')
plot(rf_perf, col='green', lwd=2, add=TRUE)

legend('bottomright', legend=c('Decision Tree', 'Random Forest', 'XGBoost'), col=c('blue', 'red', 'green'), lwd=2, cex=0.8)
